{"author":{"id":"9e708da0dcd8c03d575d27510de120e7c2b503238e176aba7ca0c33b858fd089"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1491402513,"nonce":"BqfUVlS0OIZ/yXfKWtKc8IgXKx0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI5MTg3ODk2Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1230#issuecomment-291878966"},"message":"\u003e I think that the label \"best practice\" has become incorrectly used with regard to the tools-iuc repository - it should refer only to the way the tool is written (i.e., the code). But it has somehow evolved into encompassing the functional correctness of the tool's execution, (i.e., only those tools that are labeled \"best practice\" will be functionally correct).\n\nI don't think anyone has ever said that tools not following the IUC best practices are not functionally correct. But I agree with the others that this repo should keep accepting only tools following the best practices. This is the whole point of this repo, since there is no requirement to have a tool here (or in any other repo) to submit it to the Tool Shed.\n\n\u003e I also feel that the \"best practice\" rules that pertain to the tools-iuc repository are not clear, not documented and too restrictive\n\nIUC best practices are living documents, as a member please contribute to them by opening PRs at https://github.com/galaxy-iuc/standards\n\n\u003e they require code that is more complex to write and maintain, seemingly in order to save on the number of lines\n\nThe goal is not only saving on the number of lines (which is also code we have to maintain!), but avoid parsing options twice (in Cheetah and then again in Python). Also, having a Python script means having an additional requirement.\n\n\u003e This significantly restricts the pool of tool maintainers that can participate in the tools-iuc repository.\n\nI see an increase in contributions to this repository, to the point that we are struggling to cope with them (48 open pull requests). Also, 4 new IUC members were asked to join in the last 12 months.\n\n\u003e Tools should include tests, which implies that the \"test framework\" (which may include items like Planemo or Galaxy itself) must accommodate standard Galaxy tool components like chromosome length files for genomes. Another example of a missing test framework component is handling tools that require very large inputs like scaffolds for plants. The current test framework feature that supports data tables for genome indexes does not handle these plant scaffolds since they are complex hierarchical directories of files.\n\nAll these are Galaxy/Planemo deficiencies which have nothing to do with IUC best practices.","files":null}]}